postcontent:
I have an Emperor guardian tactical shotgun that I would be interested in trading or selling.

This shotgun is in like new condition with only four shells through it. If you are not familiar with this shotgun it is made in Turkey by the same factories that make the Canik CZ75 clones and TP9, Winchester SXP, and many other quality firearms. This is a 5+1 pump action that will chamber 3 inch shells. Has a built in recoil pad and pistol grip, as well as a nice set of fiber optic ghost ring sights, a receiver mounted picatinny rail, a removable breacher choke, and is VERY lightweight. In great shape but Ive had a few shotguns with pistol grips and ring sights and Ive found that I prefer a straight stock with a bead sight. This shotgun retails for $299, Id like to trade it for a similalrly priced 12 gauge shotgun with a straight stock, bead sight, and 18-20 inch cylinder bore barrel, such as a Remington 870, Mossberg 500/maverick 88, winchester sxp, or similar. title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Model 1903 .32 ACP Series III circa 1917 Automatic pistol "like new"
location: Fenton, Hwy 44, Stanton, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Colt Model 1903 .32 ACP Series III circa 1917 Automatic pistol "like new" For a 98 year old piece of John Moses Brownings art work. The hallmark of the 1903 design was its simplicity, which helped make it the most copied pistol in the world. The only feature that might possibly be considered complex or extraneous was the grip safety, which most imitators omitted, but the 1903 was the first gun ever manufactured with a grip safety. I suspect that military feedback on the 1900 Colt Automatic Pistol had influenced Brownings design philosophy.  The pistol could also be disassembled without tools, which was another military preference.
The Model 1903 had the recoil spring beneath the barrel.  The barrel was firmly secured to the receiver by a series of lugs on the underside which mated with slots in the receiver.  
The sear, disconnector, hammer, and all springs were mounted in the receiver behind the magazine well, as was the grip safety.  The magazines hold 8 rounds. The quality of workmanship and finish on the early versions of this gun were the finest in the world at the time. The guns were heat blued and polished with oil-soaked leather. The trigger and manual safety lever were given a brilliant fire blue. Type III:  Serial numbers from 105,051 to 468,097 The primary difference in this variant was the elimination of the barrel bushing. A lug was added to the bottom front end of the barrel to keep it locked in position. At approximately serial number 114,700 the screw that retained the safety was eliminated. At some point, the slide cutout into which the barrel rotated was machined further to the rear, so the slide did not have to be retracted as far to disassemble the gun, and the takedown arrow was lengthened. In 1917 the United States Navy purchased 200 .32 caliber pocket models with serial numbers between 227,226 and 260,924 this one being 2424XX. I do not know if they received any special markings. Comes with two original, two tone magazines, zip case with pocket for the extra magazine and ammo, and the original manual that is full of all the info needed for this pistol. Please make educated offers for this 90%+ original unrestored piece of USA history, from the most accomplished firearms designer ever, RIP JMB. 
I will remove this ad when sold or traded.

The P-11 is a semi-automatic, locked-breech, DAO, pistol, chambered for the 9mm Luger cartridge. Ten round and optional twelve round magazines available. The Kel- Tec P-11 is compact and lightweight, thanks to its locked breech. Its ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. The P-11 is especially well suited for plain-clothes police officers, security personnel, or as a secondary weapon for military service members. 

The P-11 has six main component groups: barrel, slide, frame, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 Ordnance steel heat treated to 47 HRC. title: For Sale:  German SIG Sauer P229 in .40 with Action Enhancement, SRT, and More
postcontent:
For sale is a used German SIG P229 chambered in .40. It hasn't been shot much, maybe 300 rounds. The barrel and frame rails are not showing very much wear.

The gun has also gone through the SIG Custom shop for just about all they offer. I have done the following: 

*Action Enhancement Package: trigger pull is phenomenal, coming in right around 8 pounds in DA, and 4.5 in SA. The DA pull is a smooth as you can get and both modes break like glass.

*Short Reset Trigger 

*SIG Service Package, which replaced all the worn pins and springs and new sights.  

*Barrel Target Crown, and the guide rod is polished.

*Reduced Reach Trigger Installation.

All of these services combines cost over $500 according to SIG's website. The grips are also somewhat rare now as they are the aluminum slim grips made by SIG, not the new ones made by Hogue. These have a more aggressive texture to them. 

The gun will also come with the SIGLite night sights, 5 MecGar made factory mags (not the Checkmate junk), the original case, and paperwork. 

If you offer a trade, I am not interested in hunting rifles or shotguns, or .22s unless it's a SW M41, Colt Woodsman, something like that. And definitely no junk, like Hi Point, Cobra, Bryco, etc.

postcontent:
I have a Feinwerkbau Model 300 (NOT 300S ), serial # 67867.  This was made in West Germany in 1970.  It is a .177" / 4.5mm air rifle.  The condition is very good to excellent.  There are a couple tiny nicks in the wood stock by the cocking arm.  The metal is in near perfect condition, I would rate the bluing at 95%.  

This belonged to my grandfather, and I cannot recall him ever shooting it.  It has been fired though.  I test fired it recently, and it functions perfectly.  It is definitely a piece of precision engineering.  The trigger pull is unbelievably good, and I believe it is also adjustable.  This is the kind of air rifle that is/was used in the Olympics.

It comes in the original box with all of the original accessories as well as two cans of match grade pellets.  It does not come with the original manual.

If you are seriously interested in purchasing or trading for this air rifle I would welcome you to inspect it as thoroughly as you like before making any final decision.  At the very least I'm sure I would learn something.
